Nutrition for children with obesity: No breakfast and sausage for dinner
More than a third of children aged 9 to 13 are overweight; while 9 percent of school-age children are overweight, 5 percent are obese.
According to a recent study, children who suffer from obesity are usually from unhealthy families.
Once again, we see the importance of environment and patterns of behavior to a person's healthy development.
For example, sausage is nearly twice as likely to be on the tables of obese children than in families with normal-weight children.
More than 19 percent of obese children ate French fries for dinner the night before the survey, which was part of an educational event called "Obesity is not an accident".
Moreover, families with obese children do not exercise, but this is true for the majority of families with school-age children today - only 15% of children said that their parents make time to exercise at least once a week.
The study was done on 900 children.
The study was conducted at the end of last academic year; nearly 900 primary school students from all over Bohemia participated in it.
The event Obesity is not an accident was held for the second year in a row, with the support of the insurance company Všeobecná zdravotní pojišťovna and the company Unilever.
To date, more than 12,000 pupils from grades 4-8 have joined the project.
Proper nutrition and adequate exercise are the main determining factors behind the rapidly increasing number of children who are either overweight or obese.
"For example, only half of the respondents said they eat five meals a day, breakfast-breakfast-lunch-breakfast-dinner, which is a prerequisite for proper nutrition", says one study.
No lunch and sausage in the evenings.
Experts warn that even such minor details as a regular family breakfast are important for healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of school-age families eat breakfast together.
Most families have separate breakfast.
The worst finding was that one in ten families don't eat breakfast at all.
And yet, breakfast is the foundation of a healthy diet.
The study found that fried foods are more commonly consumed in families with children who are obese.
Almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sugary soft drinks every day (70%).
Although more than 40 percent of children are regularly involved in sports, this number more than doubles to 15 percent when it comes to their parents.
Make your own menu.
In another part of the study, the selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) were asked to make their own menu, based on the food they were offered and their tastes and preferences.
"The food preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 are far from ideal when it comes to healthy eating".
Their favorite foods include a large number of flour, meat and sweet dishes.
"The high popularity of sugary soft drinks is of particular concern", says the study's conclusion.
As the main meal, the pasta beat the bird with a little overweight.
However, the children showed little interest in beans, fish, or vegetables.
The pursuit of a healthy lifestyle
The study also showed that children are willing to change their eating habits if given the right information.
"Many of the control group participants showed a significant shift in preference towards healthy food when they completed the questionnaire after the lecture", the project said.
This was especially true in the case of sugary soft drinks, where more children were choosing water over sugary soft drinks.
In addition, children were more likely to choose poultry and fish as their main dishes, limiting the amount of sweet dishes and pastries.
A stylist must also be a good psychologist, say professionals
In the first article on stylist training, I complained about the amount of information in the introductory class.
I had no idea what was going to happen next.
Lectures by three experts in the field; advice on how to dress for non-standard figures; and a seminar on how all of this works in real life.
More down the road.
The closer we get to the final exam, the more information and practical assignments await us.
Training is every Saturday and Sunday, but it's really packed with information.
This time with Alenka, the principal, (there are no men in the course) we discussed how to dress a woman whose body is not perfectly symmetrical.
Most women are not completely symmetrical.
One has a short neck, another has a boyish figure without proper form, another weighs more than normal.
A stylist must know how to visually reduce the broad shoulders, lengthen the neck or add the missing volumes.
We were given advice on how to accentuate the figure of women like Jennifer Lopez, who have larger breasts and smaller hips and smaller waists, and not dress too revealingly.
For example, if the difference in waist and hip volume is so great that you can't fit a skirt or pants, you might want to have at least one item custom made.
You're not going to regret the investment, because perfectly fitting clothing is priceless.
A custom-made skirt will make you feel much better than one that's constantly falling off, rolling over, exposing your waist, and so on.
The owner of a boy's figure, on the other hand, may wear clothes with ruffles, applique, embroidery or folds.
Given the abundance of this information and the types of figures, I'm glad I have a whole week to figure it all out.
Still, I'm afraid it's a little much, considering the homework we've been given.
Each participant had to design two outfits for a celebrity: one for the day and one for the evening.
We have to consider their modern appearance, their style of clothing and their body type.
I'm going to be wearing Miranda Kerr, who you may know from Victoria's Secret commercials.
I'm happy for myself because it's much easier to wear than, say, Britney Spears, Christina Aguilera, who recently gained a ton of weight (please note that I'm exaggerating), or the very young Selena Gomez.
We have to cut clothes out of magazines or find them online, print them and then process them with graphic software.
The board of paintings, the result of the work, then reflects our own style and attitude towards the graphic.
It's important to keep in mind the graphic component of style.
The stylist does not just dress real people, but creates product pages in magazines (based on specific indications, for example, fashion bags, coats, etc.).
That's what the stylist and designer Mario Kamenick told us.
But it was only Sunday.
A stylist needs a general knowledge.
Saturday's lecture, rich with information about the types of figures, was animated by three guests who are experts in this field.
The stylist is Honza Pokorna; the fashion designer is Jacob Polanka; and the fashion photographer is Ben Renz.
Yaqub reminded us that fashion is an illusion and a stylist should take advantage of this fact.
A good stylist knows how to use the same garment in different ways.
In this case, diversity is the key to success.
For example, a trench coat can be worn casually, over jeans and T-shirts, as a coat; but it can also be worn on the bare body, without buckles, as a dress.
Another option is to roll up your sleeves or raise your collar, and the whole image changes completely.
"Play with it", he insisted.
However, the advice I appreciated most was this: "For your job, you should know the rules perfectly".
Then you can start breaking them,' Yaqub told us.
And here I finally understand why we're all so obsessed with definitions and rules, what to pair with what and why, when in fashion magazines we often see something quite different.
Not to mention the fashion shows.
I learned from Beena, a photographer, that a stylist has more outfits than she has pictures to take.
So, for a fashion review of ten pages (equivalent to ten outfits), I have to be ready to create at least fifteen images.
Now I also know that in a picture, the garment often looks and acts in combination with others quite differently than in reality.
We have to keep that in mind when we create an image.
Honza Pokorny confirmed that often image and style are half the success.
Just look at Madonna, who doesn't have a great vocal, but her image and marketing have made her a global star.
Attitude towards stylists in the Czech Republic is still quite cool.
Even famous people often find it superfluous (and believe that it is enough to be an expert in something, and how they look is secondary).
And if someone finally lets us create their style, we should expect them to name a different (smaller) size than the one they actually wear.
Then we go to Google and see if the tabloids have written anything about any celebrity getting fat, losing weight, etc.
On Sunday, Honza and Mario emphasized that it is not enough for a stylist to know fashion and be able to pick out a wardrobe.
Our job is basically to interact with the people we dress; that's why it's important to be a good psychologist.
To be able to evaluate people, not to patronize them, and to have my own opinion.
"If the manager asks you to look at her clothes and add a few beautiful things, you can't throw out her entire wardrobe by telling her that her clothes are awful".
"Find at least a few things that you can commend, and suggest what you can wear with them", Mario says.
He also showed us exactly what the work bag should hold.
It's a bag that you wrap around your waist to carry all the essentials.
In addition to the obvious things, such as scissors, a sticky roller or English pins, it should have a nylon thread (stylers use it when shooting some items, for example, a bag or a hat), special clips to fasten the fabric on the back in case the clothes are too big (the shoes and similar items are prohibited, as they spoil the clothes) or a sewing kit.
To get away from the lecture and get some practical experience, we learned how to make the right shoe soles.
Even when shooting in a studio where the floor is smooth, the soles can get damaged - not to mention shooting in the street.
So we started to glue.
You shouldn't touch the shoes with the scissors, otherwise they'll be ruined.
It takes real skill.
I was glad that Mario praised my work.
I didn't like the skills you mentioned.
This is just some of what we heard during the second half of the weekend's classes.
I'm starting to realize that being a professional stylist isn't as easy as people say.
V for Speed: Escape is set in America.
The overview
What should have been a carefree walk turned into a routine morning commute to work because of a series of completely inappropriate and careless mistakes.
The ambitions were satisfied to some extent, but it didn't matter, because no one wanted to do the extra work.
Before the new version with the subtitle "Escape" was released, there were high hopes.
It was expected to take the previous Need For Speed series in a new direction; demo versions suggested that the game would take its place in the racing game genre.
We were curious to see the part of the game where the main character gets out of the car and runs.
As is often the case with NFS, things turn out differently than we expected.
The game is a fairly good arcade racing game, but the overall impression is marred by several unnecessary bugs that have been present in this series of games for several years.
So, these are not really mistakes, but the inexplicable laziness of the developers.
The adventure starts very well.
You become part of a story in which the main character, Jack, decides to solve some personal problems by participating in an illegal race across America.
You get in a car on the West Coast, in San Francisco, and your mission is to be the first to New York.
There are some interesting aspects to this idea.
The route consists of ten stages, divided into more than fifty races.
This means that each race is run on its own course, with individual stages taking place in a diverse and interesting environment.
So it doesn't feel like the same thing is happening all the time.
Although the graphics are at the same level as in previous parts of the series, some tracks are nice to look at.
But the game doesn't evoke any strong emotions.
Although driving through the desert, the autumn suburbs, or high up in the snowy mountains is very pleasant.
And the race is occasionally brought to life by an unusual detail.
For example, in the desert, you're in a sandstorm, which significantly reduces visibility.
On the other hand, in the mountains, you have to be careful not to get caught in an avalanche.
The individual races are pretty well organized.
There are only a few varieties, but that's enough.
For a while, you try to overtake several competitors (essentially a normal race); then you try to improve your time (a standard race with a stopwatch); or you compete with one opponent.
And, of course, you run into the police from time to time, which makes your job even more difficult.
The components on the outside of the car are new.
It's just an interactive animation where most of the time Jack is running from someone and you have to help him by pressing the right buttons at the right time.
It's not that big a deal.
Although surprisingly, these fragments are much smaller than you might expect (only three to be exact).
It actually turns out that this is good for gaming, because it's a non-boring property; all things considered, it's one of the things that makes gaming more fun.
The racing model follows in the footsteps of the previous models.
It means that she's no longer special, but that's not a disadvantage.
If you're looking for a simulation of real life, you'll have to look elsewhere.
Still, this driving model is very suitable for dynamic racing, although there are better options on the market.
It's going very well so far.
But after a while, things start to go wrong.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model is not so good.
You don't expect any complicated transformations or collisions from this game, but if you have no idea before you hit the object how your car will behave, something is wrong.
Normally, when you're overtaking or passing cars in a traffic jam, you'll occasionally touch the other car slightly, and yet sometimes in a situation that's very similar, your car will start to spin wildly.
Or it was a total wreck.
It's not that important because of the reboot system, but it's enough to ruin the fun.
The restarts are designed so that if you crash or go off the track, the game will return you to the point where it stopped.
However, only five restarts are available for each race.
If you use all of them, you'll have to start the race from the beginning.
It's useful in case something doesn't work, but you can't rely on it completely.
Sometimes the restarts aren't enough, and you have to memorize a section of the race.
A major drawback of the game is the fact that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, some turns need to be done a certain way, otherwise you just don't fit in.
In other cases, you'll encounter civilian cars in a certain place in the same configuration whether you're coming first, fifth, five seconds early or a minute late.
This is especially annoying in situations where you see your opponent easily passing between two cars going in opposite directions, whereas when you get there, the cars are already in position so that you have to either pass them or slow down.
It doesn't matter when you're around them; it's designed to be right in front of your face.
The rivals have other advantages.
During the game, you discover several places where, regardless of the time, the same opponent is overtaking you in the same place.
This is especially apparent at the end of the game, on the long bridge, where you're driving in the opposite direction.
Obviously, your opponent has to stand up to you no matter what.
The thing is, when it's driving in front of you, it makes it harder to see, which leads to one or more accidents in this station.
It's understandable to try to make the game more exciting and adrenaline-filled, but it's so obvious that it quickly becomes irritating.
It's a shame, because despite the simple driving model, the game is entertaining and sometimes so full of events that you don't have time to pay attention to what's going on around you.
It doesn't matter what keeps you entertained, whether it's a concept with fifty unique tracks, a sequence of races, or something else.
The idea of changing cars during a race is unusual.
You need to keep track of the fuel tanks along the way, because that's where your car can be replaced, even though in most cases the one you already have is quite sufficient.
Cars fall into three categories.
Sports cars are for city driving; powerful American cars are for straight-track driving; and exotic super-sports are for technical driving, such as on curvy mountain trails.
The main story mode is closely related to the challenge mode; it is racing through individual sections that you learn as you play.
Here you earn for your personal case both medals and points, common to the challenges and story modes.
There are many options available to get a higher level of driving, from cars to profile data.
The profile is also linked to the online Autolog feature, which, among other things, compares your scores with those of other players, and provides a public link.
Here's another flaw that's hard to understand; this is an example from the last race in the sequence.
You and your car are in a subway tunnel (assuming that's what it is), where you're running along the tracks in the dark (assuming that's what it is).
Your speedometer is reading from 100 to 200 kilometers an hour, let's say, when suddenly a subway train comes up behind you, turning your car into a pile of junk.
For days, our editorial staff debated whether it was true that no one had given the game a second's thought, or whether the creators really thought we were such fools.
The technical aspect of the game is not particularly impressive, but the overall experience of the video game is mostly pleasant, sometimes even thrilling.
Although unfortunately, at some critical points, the quality of the recording, sometimes quite dramatically, decreases.
This is especially true in high-volume incidents where a good recording wouldn't do you much good either.
Sound is fine; soundtrack is for the amateur.
To appeal to the younger audience, the soundtrack 'includes a variety of styles'; but it is unlikely that many people will buy the game because of its music.
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run is quite messy.
If the game avoided obviously unnecessary errors, we could honestly say that Escape is the best part of NFS in the last few years.
Anyway, the game leaves a sense of incompletion.
Sure, it's fun, but be prepared to be blinded by the flaws, like an airport searchlight.
The choir of the University of Karlov will perform at the "Students in the velvet" concert
The third year running Festa Academia festival proposes to combine the International Student Day and the anniversary of the Velvet Revolution with a musical event.
He's gonna be representing about 20 school and university choirs.
The main event of the festival is two concerts, which will take place on November 17.
"Karlov University is actively involved in the festival".
"The participating choirs include the Choir of the Faculty of Pedagogy and Humanities; Václav Gumpl, Rector, will be part of the committee", said Jakub Čalún, head of the organizing committee.
The culmination will be a free public concert of school choirs, which will take place at 2pm on November 17 in the square in front of the National Technical Library in Dewitz.
The Jazz Mass by the famous Czech jazz musician Karel Ružička is also included in the program.
In the evening, the official National House in Vinograd will host a concert "Students in velvet", with the participation of university choirs, including the choirs of the Charles University.
The purpose of Festa Academica is to celebrate the International Student Day and to commemorate the 22nd anniversary of the Velvet Revolution; as well as to present good music of the highest quality to the public and to develop creative interaction among young people.
The main organizer is the českých pěveckých sborů (Czech choirs) in cooperation with the secondary school named after Johann Kepler.
The event is supported by Boguslav Svoboda, Lord Mayor of Prague, and Václav Gampl, Rector of Charles University.
The festival will take place from November 16 to 20 in Prague and Pardubice.
The program offers both official concerts and numerous musical meetings, student happenings, daytime performances, etc.
For more information please visit the website of the festival: www.festaacademica.cz
Ambassador to the EU Vitsenova:
The Czechs have a reputation for being unfriendly and skeptical of the euro.
"The Lisbon Treaty has caused considerable disagreement among the various organizations".
"I didn't expect it to be such a brutal war".
"It will take five or six years before the situation will stabilize, calm down and all the players will get used to their new roles", EU Ambassador Milena Vitenova began her lecture at the law faculty with a stern tone.
She proved her commitment to her motto, "Europe Clear and Open", in the first part of her talk, where she described the EU institutions and their relationship in a way that many UC law professors would envy.
Moreover, Vitsenova praised the work of the new permanent president of the European Council, Herman Van Rompuy:
"At first, critics said he was a plain gray office mouse who couldn't play any role; I have to say, everyone was amazed at how well he did his part".
"He is a man who can listen to 27 member countries at the same time, who is a great communicator and who has a clear idea of where the EU should go".
She explained her new post as an international relations and security representative as an answer to the question: "What is the European Union? What number should I call?"; i.e. as an important step towards unification and greater transparency of the Union's policy towards countries such as China or India.
Nobody 's going to ban our cheese .
Vitsenova then focused on the programme, which is key for the EU in the past, present and near future.
She called the Czech presidency successful in the year before last.
The Czechs were dealing with the impending financial crisis; they overcame that crisis and organized the Eastern Partnership summit.
She said that the resignation of the government at that time was a negative phenomenon that caused considerable damage to the Czech Republic.
The Czech representatives in the EU are very busy at the moment.
As the ambassador said, both the presidency and the subsequent financial crisis caused the current ferment.
And it also needs to adopt a new seven-year EU budget, which is not easy given the current crisis.
Whether the budget will be tight and sparing, which areas will be given priority; which countries will receive more support and which less; all these questions are on the agenda.
The Ambassador recalled the key slogans she had brought to Brussels: "On Europe, in a language we understand".
"I really don't like abbreviations, foreign words and jargon that no one understands.
How can citizens understand that in Brussels people are not trying to sell curly or round cucumbers, bananas of different sizes, or that someone is going to ban our cheese varieties.'
It also intends to make better use of the EU environment and to attract more Czechs to European organisations.
A multi-speed Europe is our future
The ambassador claims that the Czechs are considered to be Eurosceptics; as well as people who note the negative rather than the positive sides of things.
She wants more Czech representatives to be involved in European organizations.
She believes that this is due to several factors: for example, the modesty of our candidates and their inability to write motivational letters; at the same time with little support from the Czech side.
Along with the successful chairmanship of the Czech Republic, she noted the power and cooperation of the Visegrad Group.
"Believe me, when I meet someone from Poland or Hungary and we are joined by a Slovak, the Frenchman next to me says: 'Hey, what's the meeting about, the Visegrad Group again?' and he's not happy about it.'
In the future, the Union of Vicenova expects mainly new strict rules for the budget policy of the member states.
Compared with the new European Federation, she sees the idea of a two-speed, if not multi-speed Europe as more realistic.
"We have countries both inside and outside the Eurozone".
"We have the Schengen area, and we already have the institute of enhanced cooperation".
"It was said for the first time that countries that wanted to join should join, while those that didn't wanted to join could stay out".
"The number of such institutions will grow; it will be a truly two-speed Europe", Vitsenov expects.
In this respect, she underlined the role of both the Czech Republic and Herman Van Rompuy in promoting the rule that all issues concerning the EU as a whole should be discussed by all member countries, not just those in the eurozone.
The story of the brand:
The pioneer IBM is entering its second century.
If someone wants to find a word that best expresses the strategy of IMB, the closest one will probably be "durable".
To the general public, IBM is a symbol of the technological revolution; the company is considered very modern, although it was founded more than a hundred years ago.
The company's longevity was laid down by its first boss, the dreamer Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He believed in his motto that many of the world's problems could be solved easily if people would just think.
His slogan "Think!" thus became the stamp around which the future giant's life revolved (as well as the name of his internal magazine, which IMB began publishing in 1935).
Moreover, it was the foundation of the corporate culture that Watson had carefully built.
"For us at IBM, long-term thinking means constantly moving into the future.
IBM survived and prospered for a hundred years because it remained true to its original values, while not being afraid to change everything around it.
In our first hundred years, it has enabled us to transform technology, business and society.
In the next 100 years, we hope to achieve even more", says Samuel J. Palmisano, the company's current president, on the occasion of the anniversary.
A complex system
In the 1930s, Watson approached the issue of caring for employees in the same way that Batya did in the Czech Republic - IMB employees were among the first American employees with paid leave, employer insurance, elegant uniforms, and a sophisticated bonus system for the best inventors and entrepreneurs.
Equally advanced are IBM's long-term relationships with consumers.
From the very beginning, the company has found brilliant use for talented people, and it was one of the first companies in the world to eliminate all discrimination, which gave it a great choice.
Consistent with the anti-discrimination strategy and the current plan, a woman, Virginia Rometti, will replace Palmisano next year.
She worked at IBM for thirty years; she is currently the director of sales, marketing and development.
For the last few years, IBM has been hosting meetings, online brainstorming sessions, where many of the innovations of the future are born.
It's no wonder that there are so many ideas - the company employs about half a million people.
An organization with a good reputation
A strong position in business is ensured by a strong internal and external image.
"From the beginning, IBM was conceptually more of an organization than a technology company", Harvard Business School professor and IBM author Rosabeth Moss Kanter told The Economist.
"IBM is not a technology company, it's a company that helps solve business problems with technology", adds George Coloney of Forrester Research.
As the company itself says, there's a difference between going to market and creating a market.
In a hundred years, IBM, or the Blue Giant, as it is known in the United States because of its logo, has become one of the largest companies in the world.
It seems to be the most all-inclusive technology company -- hardware and software, infrastructure, hosting and consulting, everything from servers to nanotechnology.
It holds the most patents of any American technology company, and five of its employees have won Nobel Prizes.
Her inventions include, for example, the ATM, the bank card, the financial swap, the barcode and the floppy disk.
With $220 billion in market capitalization, IBM is the second-largest technology company this year, overtaking Microsoft for the first time since 1996.
Looking ahead
Not all of its products were to the taste of customers and fit the era. For example, IBM failed with its OS/2 operating system; online service Prodigy and IBM PCjr computers.
"If your business is defined by moving forward, you can't be emotionally attached to the past", says Samuel J. Palmizano.
That's why IBM is so easy to build on multiple platforms -- if they don't work, they'll drop them.
This is how it differs, for example, from its competitor Microsoft, which is based and survives the fall on Windows, its operating system.
The future of technology
IBM's main revenue comes from services, with about one-fifth of each coming from computer software and hardware.
In 1990, with half the capital, it was the strongest hardware company.
Since 2000, IBM has sold $15 billion of its undervalued assets, while investing $58 billion in promising technology.
It continued to invest even after 2008, when the world was first hit by the current economic crisis.
IBM follows the example of its first CEO, Thomas J. Watson, who increased investment during the Great Depression.
So far, IBM seems to have been spared the current crisis.
Since the beginning of 2008, IBM's stock price has risen a record 120 percent; the company's net income has been steadily rising.
IBM's corporate motto is to change everything but its own values.
So it's to be expected that even if another crisis breaks out, this flexible giant will be able to handle the situation.
The story of IBM: from the cheese knife to space flight.
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago, and its original name, "Computing, Tabling, Recording Corporation", was a bit of a conundrum.
It took the name IBM in 1924, originally a brand name used for the company's branches in Canada and South America.
The foundation of the future IBM was laid by the merger of four companies, whose history began in the 1880s.
They had technologies like the legendary "table clock", a clock that recorded when employees were coming and going from work.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlet Flint, who also headed the company's board of trustees until 1930.
Flint hired a rival company's director, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
Then the CEO pushed the IBM founder into the shadows - Watson's ideas remain the foundation of an unshakable corporate culture and identity.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name implies, began by manufacturing and selling a variety of business equipment, from cheese knives and butcher knives to cash register machines.
During Watson's first four years, revenues doubled to $9 million, and the company began a massive expansion into every continent.
Watson became so important to the company that almost forty years later his son, Thomas Watson, Jr., took his place in the director's chair.
Under his leadership, IBM began to develop artificial intelligence technologies and created the first programming language.
In the 1960s, both IBM employees and computers helped NASA control space flights to Mercury, Saturn, and in 1969 a man on the moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers - the IBM line System/360.
The classic PC that defined the computing standards of the day, called the IBM 5150, came on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, simultaneously buying the consulting division of PricewaterhouseCoopers, thus concentrating entirely on consulting and high value-added services.
IBM has made great strides in the last three years with their Smarter Planet concept.
Its goal is to use technology wisely in areas where it has not been planned, and to improve the road situation and urban governance.
In the commercial space, IBM recently introduced the Smarter Commerce platform, which helps businessmen monitor the entire sales cycle.
The IBM tradition is strong even in our country.
In the former Czechoslovakia, the first country to be located in both central and eastern Europe, IBM established its branch in 1932.
Today, IBM CZ also operates a strategic outsourcing centre in Brno.
The Central and Eastern European headquarters are located in Prague, where a world-class speech recognition research team is also located.
