Price dynamics for travel since 1989
Until 1989, only five state-owned tourist agencies were allowed to operate in the former Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Since travel to the West was severely restricted, travel agencies of the time mainly sold tours to the countries of the socialist bloc.
Thus, Czech tourists went on vacation to the German Democratic Republic; the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea on the Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (both countries on the Black Sea); and Hungary (Balatón).
The only exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when we had the opportunity to travel to Yugoslavia, and then the Yugoslav regime turned to the West, which resulted in significant restrictions on Czech tourists traveling to Yugoslavia.
A big paradox of the socialist period was that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. and Czechoslovakia) were not allowed to travel individually to socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to go by himself, for example, to the Soviet Union or Poland, an invitation letter from that country was necessary; otherwise, an individual trip was impossible.
Back then, travel agencies offered trips to the West, but you had to either stand in line all night with a sleeping bag or have "good friends" at the agency.
And that's not all.
A currency permit was required for travel to the West, and it was not issued to politically unreliable people who were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not freely convertible; without a currency permit it was impossible to obtain funds (Western currency) for travel to the West.
Most Czechs spent their holidays at home, which led to the emergence of a large number of cottages and summer houses, this habit has been preserved to this day.
After 1989, tourism in the Czech Republic thus experienced a real revolution.
While before 1989 holidays to the GDR or Bulgaria were the highlight of our travels, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays in countries around the world.
The great paradox that we no longer realize is that until 1989, we couldn't freely visit the now most popular of Croatia, because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
In the early 1990s, the abolition of visa requirements for neighboring Western European countries triggered a huge wave of short-term travel, mainly to Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks couldn't get enough of travelling to the West, everyone wanted to go there for a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech tourists slept in parks in tents, as their income at the time was not enough for a hotel or a boarding house.
A typical feature of Czech tourism at that time was the desire to bring their own food (cans, salami, etc.) to save money.
Another important point is the introduction of the freely convertible Czech krona, which after decades our tourists can finally buy Western currency freely.
Our standard of living and average income were rising, which around 1997 led to another important circumstance.
Since 1997, increased demand has allowed travel agencies to arrange regular flights operated by charter airlines. Compared to the past, flights have now become incredibly cheap thanks to the ability to order wholesale discounts.
By the late 1990s, Czechs did not need a visa to visit almost all developed countries in the world except the United States, which made our travels even easier.
The next significant event in the history of post-revolution travel occurred in 2000 when a huge demand led to the first ever direct charter flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country, Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights have been taking Czech tourists to warm exotic countries, and this winter, flights from the Czech Republic will be taking them to twelve exotic destinations.
Now, about 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
And another important event of this period, symbolizing our development after the revolution, happened in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the United States lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, permanently adding our country to the ranks of the most developed countries in the world.
For the first time in history in 2008, Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%); and for the first time in history they spent more than 15 thousand kroner per person for holidays abroad, including their expenses at the destination.
The General Assembly must elect a president, the threat of the duck returns.
Czech football has been without a president for nearly five months, and there is a risk that the successor of Ivan Hášek, the head of the Czech Football Association (FAČR), will not be named even after another extraordinary general meeting, which will take place in Nymburk on Tuesday.
There is still no agreement on what election rules to follow.
Without it, the voting for one of the three candidates will not begin.
Yintzi Reichl, Miroslav Pelta and Tomáš Pazlík are all eager to lead the Czech football.
Ghasek left his post in June, and as he left, he urged his colleagues to unite and find a strong personality to lead football in the future.
However, the Gashek era has again plunged football into a feud between the two chambers of the association, which cannot choose a single candidate.
This became quite apparent on September 16, when a new president had to be elected.
The delegates of the general assembly had come to the National House in Prague, Smíchov, in vain, as the negotiations remained blocked, not only by the election procedure.
There was no agreement on who had the right to vote at the general meeting - only legal representatives or also officials who had been given powers of attorney.
This point has since been partially resolved by the recommendation of the Institute of State and Law, according to which representation based on delegated powers is impossible.
Disputes over the election rules, however, continue.
The Executive Council has not been much help either, although in its meetings, both regular and special, it is mainly concerned with this issue.
The idea of voting has changed several times, but the core issue remains the same.
The question is, how do we move on to round three and avoid a tie?
"The issue is whether to follow the established norms or to find another model", says one of the vice-presidents of FAČR, Dushan Svoboda, who represents professional football in the association's management.
Based on the model provided by the statute, the winner of the 3rd round is the candidate who has received the most support from the chamber from which he is a candidate.
Moravia is said to have agreed to a compromise - to consider the winner of the election the candidate with the largest number of votes in both chambers.
The Czech side insists on the condition that the overall winner must have at least two-thirds of the votes.
"However, the two previous rounds would then have lost their meaning; it would have completely rejected the concept of two chambers", Svoboda agrees with Moravia's arguments, saying it would be better not to change the rules and vote according to the existing norms.
Somewhat unexpectedly, Tomasz Paczlik agrees with his opinion, although according to estimates, the election rules, defined by the charter, suit Pelt more than other candidates.
"I would like the elections to be held as much as possible according to the statute".
"I want to avoid all the representative stupidity as in the previous general meeting", says the owner of Victoria Plzen, who is a first-time candidate; and in his statements he mainly contradicted Pelt.
Pelta remains an optimist.
He believes that the new president will be known in Nymburk; he also hopes that in the future the candidates will cooperate constructively.
"All the emotional heat will be calm after today's expected departure of the national team for the European Championship".
"Football will be on a happy wave again, people will be more willing to cooperate", says Jablonec's spokesman, who has the most experience in football management at both professional and regional levels of the three candidates.
Reichl is more reserved.
"I hope to reach an agreement, but the situation is very ambiguous".
"It's not between representatives of Bohemia and Moravia, but there are attempts to deliberately adapt the rules".
"It could cause another general meeting disruption".
"I hope that common sense will prevail", Reichl said.
There's not much time left for the parties to reach an agreement.
According to some reports, separate negotiations took place directly in Montenegro; but who knows if a football unity will be achieved before the match.
An additional flight, which was supposed to take Vice-Presidents Dalibor Kuchera and Reichl to Podgorica, did not depart Prague this morning due to a technical malfunction, and was looking for an alternative to take part of the executive committee to the venue of the replay match.
In the end, the ministerial meeting that is expected on Wednesday could prove decisive.
Education, Youth and Sports Minister Josef Dobes wants the rivals in the strongest sports association in the country to come to an agreement.
Much is at stake: government subsidies; football's creditworthiness; and a planned general assembly of ČSTV with a new directorate of Czech sports after Sazka's financial problems.
