The smart crows fill the cities
The gray squirrel is considered a problem bird in many places, and experts now say that these highly intelligent birds will never be driven out of cities.
Crowes have been part of the urban landscape for centuries, but the number of residents complaining about dirt and noise is growing in many communities.
The solution to the bird problem, however, is far from over.
At the first crow symposium in the East Frisian town of Lehr, experts argued that crow crowding was no longer possible.
Experts from all over Germany discussed possible solutions.
Finding alternatives in cities
Conservationists argued that the root of the problem in cities was the migration of highly protected wild boars, pointing out that the use of chemicals in agriculture was increasingly destroying traditional habitats.
The hunting, expanding construction, and cutting of traditional nesting trees have made life difficult for the birds.
The crows are under guard.
In the city of Zest in Westphalia and in the northwest in Yever, Dipholtz, Achim near Bremen and Lera there are large colonies, numbering more than 600 parent pairs.
The controversial project to shoot crows in the Lera caused unflattering headlines in 2005.
Critics described the trapping and beating of the birds with sticks as particularly cruel.
"Relatively moving and scaring is not going to do any good", said architect and landscape designer Werner Klewer of Leer.
The knocking down of nests by a stream of water or the cutting down of trees often has unwanted consequences, said environmental expert Manfred Keiser of Lara, Baden-Württemberg.
"The animals are dispersing, and the larger colonies are dividing and spreading to other areas".
Scare tactics are only possible in exceptional circumstances near hospitals, nursing homes and schools.
"We're going to have to live with them.
"The problem of urban areas will not be solved if they are cut off from the surrounding areas", says Mayor Lera Wolfgang Kellner.
A combination of scaring birds away from protected residential areas and encouraging them to return to other areas could be the solution.
"Information booths instead of petrol pumps" was the slogan proposed by psychologist and ethnologist Uto Maria Jurgens, who advocates a completely different approach to birds. "We must be confident to live with this problem".
Jurgens was one of the founders of the educational crow route in Ascherberg in Schleswig-Holstein, where information about the life of very intelligent crows is given on information stands.
The project is already attracting tourists.
Jurgens also expressed her opinion on complaints about the noise made by birds: "The noise conveys a lot of information.
The intelligence and cunning of these birds have become legendary, and the grizzly often not only use tools to capture prey, but also make their own.
Behavioral researchers at the University of Cambridge recently tested the intelligence of birds on four scales.
In one experiment, the birds quickly learned that they had to knock on the board to get a moth larva.
Without much training, they knew the size and shape of the stone needed to bring down the board.
In another experiment, the smartest monkeys had to solve a more difficult problem.
The researchers placed a small bucket of moth larvae inside a vertical cylinder.
The birds couldn't get their prey with their beaks.
But the researchers gave them pieces of wire.
All four birds used the wire to make hooks and used the hooks to hook the bucket to the handle and pull it out of the cylinder.
Three of the four guys got it on their first try.
