Mass Murder - The Human Dimension
Peter Englund's tense and very good new book, "The Beauty and the Sorrow: A Personal History of World War I", begins with a long list of characters that makes the heart race.
Here's a tip for how to read further: Carefully cut this page and use it as a bookmark.
You will get to know these people very closely as Mr. Englund narrates, and this list of actors will be your GPS, your beacon in those moments when, like one of these men and women, you stumble and get lost in the fog of war.
Mr Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
The book he's writing now is unusual, he describes it, quite accurately, as "a work on anti-history".
It contains few famous names, important treaties, or famous battles; there are few ambassadors, cunning journalists, or discussions of tactics and military equipment.
It is not so much a book about what happened, he explains, but "a book about what it was like". It is about "feelings, impressions, experiences, and states of mind".
The book "Beauty and Sorrow" weaves together the experiences of 20 more or less unremarkable men and women from both sides of the front line, from schoolgirls and botanist scientists to mountaineers, doctors, ambulance drivers and civil servants.
Some of these people are gonna be heroes.
Some will be captured, lose an arm or a leg, go mad or die.
Their lives are flickering here like church candles, new ones being added to many others, and some being extinguished in the meantime.
Mr. Englund's book is a departure from the standard of history books.
It's also a correction to the notion that World War I was just a heavy trench warfare on the Western Front.
"Beauty and Sorrow" skillfully gives a panorama of other theaters of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
The soldiers in this book are being swarmed by beehives; one of them is celebrating Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; the unsolved problem is the flying saucer.
It's an exciting book, almost from the beginning.
War is sweeping over these people's lives like a natural disaster, like Hurricane Katrina, smelling of smokeless gunpowder.
When you hear a cannon shot in the distance and you're a woman at home with your children, will you stay put or will you run?
Who's coming anyway?
Almost no one understands what's going on or why we're fighting this war.
"The lack of facts", notes Mr. Englund, "is filled with guesswork, conjecture, hope, fear, obsession, conspiracy, dreams, nightmares and rumors".
"Beauty and Sorrow" follows the fortunes of such people as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor in the German High Seas Fleet.
Their stories are mostly taken from memoirs, letters and other published material.
The stories of their lives can be frightening or exciting, but they are supremely alive thanks to the minute moments and the riveting detail Mr. Englund has collected.
Many of them are about deprivation and how to cope with it.
He tells the story of a German schoolgirl, and says, "Erzse, everywhere Erzse".
"Fake aluminum, fake rubber, paper bandages, wooden buttons" and so on and so on.
He keeps talking about the ersatz food in Germany.
He describes "meat made of pressed rice, boiled in lamb fat (and decorated with a fake bone made of wood); tobacco made of dried roots and dried potato skins; shoes pressed with wood".
He notes that there were "837 registered meat substitutes allowed in the production of sausage, 511 registered coffee substitutes".
Some stories are about honor and courage.
One American, feeling a strong urge for cruelty, said of war: "You feel that, after all, that's what men were made for, not to sit in comfortable armchairs with a cigarette and a whisky, an evening paper or a best-seller, and claim that this show is civilization and that your straw-jacketed shirt is not a barbarian".
The British soldier, on the other hand, sees that he will most likely die and no one will notice or feel sorry for him.
"When one is resigned to the idea of self-sacrifice, one would like to think that it would be in public", he writes.
But it's the opposite, it's like "a condemned man being hanged in secret".
Other remarks concern the old Europe that is falling apart and the new kinds of fear.
"The conflict was increasingly becoming an economic competition", writes Mr. Englund, "a factory war".
He notes the arrival of what he calls "a new species in the bestiary of the new century: a beautifully articulate and ideologically committed mass murderer in a well-sewn suit who stages a massacre from behind a desk".
People act in unpredictable ways: there are as many vile acts as there are heroic ones.
Mr. Englund told me about soldiers who tried to get venereal disease from prostitutes to avoid the front.
"The most grotesque expression of this can be seen in the trade in honorifics, which soldiers bought and smeared on their genitals in the hope of getting into the hospital", he writes.
"The desperate rubbed it in the eyes, often resulting in lifelong blindness".
Translated from the Swedish by Peter Graves, Mr. Englund's prose is flexible, but unfussy, perfectly suited to his humanistic task.
In dozens of small scenes, he shows how the war "has unleashed forces beyond all control: extreme nationalism, social revolution, religious hatred".
People are starting to ask why their leaders are making them fight.
The best books about World War I were often indirect, like Paul Fassel's The Great War and Modern Memory, or novels like Erich-Marie Remarque's On the Western Front Without Change, rather than exhaustive historical works.
Mr. Englund's book is part of this unconventional pantheon.
His book has the most amazing ending I can think of in nonfiction.
I'm not going to tell it.
But it's like he reached out of a book and pulled up a character list, and he took it out of your hand and lit it with a match.
