The school service union is suing the city for layoffs .
The union, which represents hundreds of school-service staff who lost their jobs last month, plans to sue the city on Wednesday, claiming the firings were unnecessary and were discriminatory because of the disproportionate impact on schools where poor students attend.
A lawsuit is probably the last resort available to the 37th District Council union trying to overturn the layoffs.
Six hundred and seventy-two school assistants, parent-coordinators and other employees, who were among the city's lowest-paid workers, lost their jobs on October 7 as a result of what union leaders called a political backlash over their refusal to give the city access to health funds run by labor groups to close a budget gap last spring.
City officials have flatly denied the charge.
At a City Council hearing last month, school chancellor Dennis M. Walcott said the layoffs were part of the budget they signed in June.
One of the board members countered by telling him that there was no provision in the budget for the school support staff to be fired.
Representatives of the 37th District Council said they had filed a notice of claims, notifying the Department of Education that a lawsuit had been filed against it; a press conference will be held on Wednesday to announce the formal filing of the lawsuit in the state Supreme Court in Manhattan.
The lawsuit will name Mr. Walcott and the city's education department as defendants and list eight temporary-said employees as plaintiffs, all of whom are black or Hispanic women, as well as most of the assistants who lost their jobs.
Elizabeth Thomas, a spokeswoman for the city's legal department, said the city has not seen the lawsuit and therefore cannot comment on its specific provisions.
According to a preliminary version of the complaint obtained by The New York Times, the union focused on a number of school layoffs in the city's poorest neighborhoods to support its claims of unfair treatment, claiming that poor schools lost more assistants because they were chronically underfunded.
He points out that while there were no layoffs in Staten Island and few in Upper East Side or Tribeca schools, 17 school support workers lost their jobs in District 23 in Brownsville, Brooklyn, and 46 had to leave in Districts 8 and 9 in the South Bronx.
Noting the loss of five of the eight school assistants who worked at the free middle school 36 in Harlem, where 68 percent of students live in poverty, the lawsuit says, "These are not neighborhoods of wealthy parents who can find money to make up for budget shortfalls".
P.S. The 36th District's budget was cut by 3.26 percent this year, and it also lost money when the city changed the way it calculates supplemental funding for every poor student who enters the school.
The union also alleges that school principals may have been misled by the language of the notice allowing the dismissal of the parent coordinators.
