"Sixty-six parent-coordinators were fired", the lawsuit states, "and not just transferred".
Mission accomplished, Congress ready to settle Libya.
It seems that Republicans and Democrats on Capitol Hill are finally ready to agree on something having to do with the Libyan uprising.
All it took was for the rebellion to succeed, for the long-time dictator Muammar Gaddafi to be captured and killed, and for the American intervention to be over.
On Tuesday, the Senate Foreign Relations Committee is set to consider a resolution put forward by Chairman John Kerry (D-Mass.) along with Senators John McCain (R-A) and Joseph I. Lieberman (Independent, Conn.) that would praise the Libyans for their successful uprising and the American troops for their "courage".
"The purpose of this resolution is to pay tribute to the brave people of Libya as they begin to rebuild their country", Kerry said.
"It's a testament to their democratic aspirations from both parties".
The language may seem harmless, but no discussion of Libya has ever been easy.
This summer, lawmakers from both parties argued with each other and with the White House over the wording of a series of resolutions endorsing or condemning the role of the US military in the NATO mission in Libya.
In June, Kerry and McCain introduced a resolution allowing limited use of U.S. military forces in Libya.
The bill was rejected by the House of Representatives by a significant majority of both parties and never made it to a vote in the Senate.
But on the same day that the bill failed in the House of Representatives, the House also failed to support a proposal that would have cut funding for the American operation in Libya.
It has left the American mission in a sort of legislative purgatory - where Congress is angry enough to criticize Obama's approach to the mission, but not so angry that it actually kicks the soil out from under its feet.
Then events overtook the Congress ' indecision .
In August, Tripoli surrendered to Libyan rebels, and on October 20, Gaddafi was killed.
The NATO mission officially ended on October 31.
Now the Senate can be ready to act.
The Foreign Affairs Committee resolution "admires the Libyan people for their incredible courage and extraordinary steadfastness in the pursuit of freedom" and thanks the men and women of the United States Armed Forces and their coalition partners who participated in the military operation to protect the Libyan people for their extraordinary courage and professionalism".
The resolution also "affirms the national interest of the United States in a successful and irreversible transition to democracy in Libya".
Will the new measures gain the full support of the Council on Foreign Relations or split lawmakers like June's bill?
The latter version was opposed by Senator Richard G. Luger, the Republican leader on the committee.
A spokesman for Luger said Monday that he had not yet seen the final version of the bill.
On the other side of the Capitol, the House of Representatives is due to vote this week on a constitutional amendment calling for a balanced budget, a top legislative priority for nearly every Republican and for some Democrats in Congress.
This measure, proposed by Rep. Bob Goodlatte (R-Virginia), will be the first constitutional amendment on a budget or anything else to be put to a vote by this year's full Congress.
Other lawmakers have failed to get their amendments through the floor, but it's not because they haven't tried.
The Goodlat amendment is just one of 68 constitutional amendments covering a wide range of issues that were introduced in this session.
Some were duplicated - the same bill was introduced in the House and the Senate - others were minor variations of each other.
There are at least 15 versions of the balanced budget amendment in the House of Representatives alone and a few more on "control of federal spending".
Some of them are identical, but they give their authors -- mostly newly elected Republicans who want to embellish their resumes -- a chance to brag about having "picked up" such a proposal.
The Budget Control Act, which passed in August, required that both the House and Senate vote on a balanced budget amendment.
In March, 58 senators voted for a non-binding resolution supporting the idea of such an amendment.
In addition to the budget, some congressmen want to limit the number of terms of office for members of Congress, and House member Jose Serrano (D-NY) wants to remove the two-term limit for the president.
Congressman Jesse L. Jackson, Jr. (Democrat, Illinois) has proposed a number of amendments that guarantee, among other things, the right to quality education and health care.
The amendment banning same-sex marriage has been proposed for years, as has the one banning flag burning.
Some lawmakers also want to allow federal laws to be overturned if two-thirds of the states object.
As eager as members of Congress are to propose amendments, they are not moving any faster than in previous years.
In the 111th Congress, lawmakers proposed 77 such amendments, and in the 110th Congress, they introduced 66.
This pace pales in comparison to the early 1990's, when members of Congress regularly proposed more than 150 amendments every two years, according to the Library of Congress.
But they were no more successful than they are now.
The last amendment that was passed, the 27th, was approved in 1992, but it was actually introduced in Congress in 1789.
