Walls have eyes: How researchers study you on Facebook
Before he became the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just another guy who was putting his anti-immigration views online.
On Monday, Breivik, who confessed to committing the mass murder in Norway in July that killed 77 people, appeared in his first public court hearing.
While Breivik could have acted alone, he was far from alone in the network: he spent a lot of time preparing for the attack at his computer, communicating with millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social media.
After the summer tragedy, researchers wanted to know more about these people.
But how do we find them?
It's easy, you just need to go on Facebook.
"We found it was very easy to get to them", says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recently published report on European cyberpopulism by the UK-based DEMOS research centre.
Facebook's personal data pool is so large, Bartlett says, that researchers could easily use the site's advertising tool to target the right demographic with scientific accuracy - something marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million right-wing fans across Europe and then pushed ads to them, but instead of showing a new group or diet product, the ads invited the user to take a survey that asked questions about their level of education, attitudes toward violence and optimism about their own future.
Using Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to survey more than 10,000 members of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - without even leaving their offices.
"This is a whole new way of doing research", says Bartlett.
Some of the results are not so striking: the online supporters of right-wing groups are mostly young men who are unhappy with immigration.
But suddenly, "those who combine their online and offline activities are smarter, more democratic and less aggressive than those who hide behind a screen".
DEMOS' work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming a new popular tool in the hands of scientists.
Research institutes, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study everything from health issues to social trends that are expressed in 'likes' and wall posts and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three posts per day, Facebook's "super-recent news" has been driving a research boom, increasing the number of scientific articles with the site's name in the headline by 800% in the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it allows you to study people that you can't reach on the street with a notebook.
"In the past, if you wanted to interview people from the British National Party, it would have been very difficult to identify them".
"You'd have to join the party, and they'd never accept you", says Bartlett.
"Facebook is excluding all of this - you're going directly to them".
Others say that the site could be used to identify and research social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues found that students who discussed their drunken exploits on Facebook were significantly more at risk of alcoholism than students who were silent about them.
Moreno suggests that peers of students, such as their dorm room mentors, could monitor the site and intervene to help a student who updates his drunk status too often.
"You can't solve a problem without identifying it", Dimitri Christakis, Moreno's co-author and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Children's Research Institute in Seattle, told The Washington Post.
"We found a way to identify children at risk who would otherwise not have been detected".
Facebook also constantly extracts all kinds of data about its users.
The site's data processing team has processed statistics on relationship status and Valentine's Day, midterm voter turnout in 2010, and the National Happiness Index (mainly using information only they have access to - champions of cyberfreedom have long insisted that the site should make its extensive data collection publicly available for research).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them whether they like it or not -- in exchange for the ability to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away, the site can process your personal data.
But what if Facebook users become part of a study they don't even know about?
While researchers have strict rules for conducting offline research, online data is open to the public.
"I don't think many users have even thought about the fact that a researcher could be looking at their profile", says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, of a study he conducted in 2006 using publicly available student Facebook pages.
"As far as they were concerned, it was just between them and their friends".
Then there's the question of methodology.
Even offline, there's no guarantee that the subject of the study is completely honest.
There's no way to know on Facebook how much of a user's profile and page is real.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do off Facebook are two completely different things", says Selvin.
That's why, despite his years of technological research, Selvin thinks that a notebook and a pen are still the best research tools you can use.
"There's no substitute for going out into the real world and interacting with real people", he says.
"Social research is supposed to be about social, and a lot of social still happens offline".
