Seven lessons from the lost Steve Jobs interview that's playing in theaters this week.
After Steve Jobs' death on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford, describing the tech genius as the Great Inventor of Modernity.
But what Apple fans might consider the biggest revelation in the newly rediscovered interview that was recalled in anticipation of previews in major markets this week is how much this creative genius understood about business processes and manufacturing technologies.
He was, of course, a designer, a dreamer, and a self-described hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and modernizationist who believed that many business executives suffered from "the disease of thinking that a really great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] a great idea is separated from a great product by a tremendous amount of skilled labor".
Back in 1995, Bob Kringle was creating the TV series Triumph of the Nerds about the advent of the personal computer, and he spent over an hour with Jobs in a unique long conversation.
By that time, it had been about 10 years since Jobs was fired from Apple, and he was already working full-time at his new computer company, NeXT, in anticipation of the mass adoption of the Internet.
While a small portion of Kringle's interview was used in Nerds, he says the original interview was lost in transit.
It wasn't until after Jobs' death that a complete VHS copy was found in the director's garage.
This footage, slightly edited, is the basis for the 68-minute film Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which is being released at Landmark Theaters this Wednesday and Thursday.
For a man known for his hatred of in-depth interviews, Jobs seems unusually ready to lay out his technology philosophy and business strategy here.
And incredibly resourceful.
There are four different moments during the interview where there are long intervals between questions and answers -- 10-15 second reflections, where Jobs is clearly weighing his thoughts to be more precise.
There are also moments where Jobs' perfectionism comes to the surface, where he seems to be annoyed by Kringle's questions, forcing him to move quickly to questions or events of greater importance.
In this pre-Pixar, iPod, and iPhone era, "Lost Interview", there's something eerily prophetic as Jobs assesses what he sees different companies doing right and wrong, and offers his own vision of the future of information technology.
