About the Pope joke:
Jobs details the "blue box" he built with Steve Wozniak, a device that allowed people to effectively hack into the phone company and make long-distance calls for free.
The device has been written about a lot before, but Jobs' euphoria here in describing the blue box as an act of empowerment is infectious.
He tells how he and Wozniak tested the box by using a pay phone, ordering a call and then connecting from one AT&T network to another until they connected as many stations as possible.
"We circled the globe half a dozen times, and you yelled into the pay phone, and a minute later it was in the next pay phone", Jobs says with a smile.
"We were young, and all we learned was that we could engineer something that could control billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world".
We both knew little, but we could engineer a little thing that could control a big thing, and that was an incredible lesson, and I don't think Apple could have ever come into existence without it.
Jobs goes on to detail one famous stunt that he and Wozniak practically pulled off, calling the Vatican through a blue box at midnight and asking for the Pope's phone, trying their best to copy Henry Kissinger.
When various members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak with an American diplomat, these two broke out laughing just before the Pope himself was taken up to answer the phone.
On being in love with technology (and Bill Hewlett's cold-called-out-of-the-box-of-the-world):
At age 12, while hunting for spare parts to build a frequency meter, he found Bill Hewlett in the telephone directory and called him.
Shortly after their 20-minute phone call, Jobs got a summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"It had a profound effect on me, it was the only company I had seen at that age, and it shaped my view of what a company is and how well they treat their employees".
Jobs later became one of the HP employees who visited the company's Palo Alto research labs, where he saw "the very first desktop computer".
It was the size of a suitcase, it had a little monitor with an e-ray tube, and I fell in love with it.
I used to go to HP as a teenager and hang around that machine and write programs for it.
On the improvised innovation:
In several of the interviews, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the fly.
At the dawn of his career, when he was off to sell a handful of circuit boards, one buyer asked him to assemble an entire computer.
Working on a 30-day loan, he had to think about both assembling and delivering the finished devices.
Later at Apple, he recalled the difficulties he faced while developing a computer mouse:
"I remember the fierce arguments... they were yelling at me that it would take five years [to build a mouse that would cost $300], and I was fed up, and I went out and found a designer".
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could put together for $15 that was incredibly reliable.
The big companies that are wasting energy:
Long before he led Apple's renaissance, Jobs had foreseen that many of the industry's leaders would misjudge the situation and lose control of their market share.
"Suppose you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make the best copier or printer, and what?"
You have a monopoly on the market, so the company doesn't get any more success.
Sales and marketing make it more successful, so [these are the types of people] who end up in the leadership of companies, and the people who make the product are pushed out of the decision-making platform.
The genius of the product that led to this monopoly position is being pushed out by people who have no idea of the difference between good and bad products - the skill required.
That's what happened with Xerox...
Xerox could take over the entire IT industry.
It could be ten times bigger, it could be the Microsoft of the '90s...
They got a defeat out of a win.
On innovation as an art form:
"The great idea is separated from the great product by a great amount of hard work... when you promote a great idea, it changes and grows".
You'll learn a lot about her subtleties.
There are trade-offs you have to make -- some things you can't make electrons or glass or robots or factories do.
You have to keep 5,000 ideas in your head, these concepts, and link them all together...
It's ultimately about taste -- it's about trying to express yourself in the best way that humans have ever done, and then later -- trying to bring that into what you do.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We've always been ashamed of stealing great ideas.
Part of what made Macintosh famous was that the people who worked on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who happened to be the best information technology experts in the world.
If it wasn't for information technology, they would be doing amazing things in other fields.
