How to Catch a Liar
A quick glance at recent headlines shows how serious and pervasive deception and lies are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy disputing sexual harassment allegations against several women; each side accusing the other of lying.
The University of Pennsylvania was charged with perjury for allegedly concealing the fact that a retired football coach had raped the boys.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught on the mic, telling US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
Lies destroy careers and shake countries.
New York Congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made a fool of himself by denying his antics, which was quickly refuted by compelling evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign finance fraud, involving the concealment of extramarital affairs.
And again, no one living at the time will ever forget the media circus with President Bill Clinton being caught lying about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky during his second term in office.
Stories of cheating on exams at school and college are common.
There were times when teachers gave students answers to tests so that they could have a good sense of their own performance.
The teachers who are supposed to teach the opposite are sending a message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How many lies are we exposed to?
Research shows that you can be lied to from 10 to 200 times in a single day.
Now it's assumed that a significant part of that is a lie to save lives.
Another study found that strangers lied to each other three times within 10 minutes of meeting each other.
Detecting a lie or exposing a lie is a skill everyone needs for both personal and professional purposes.
Unlike the room game, like a charade, where you have to say, "I got you!" lie detection is a serious area of knowledge, based on scientific data collected over the last six decades at prestigious universities, engaged in comprehensive research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One result of the study is that most of the old myths about lying have been debunked.
Liars look people in the eye.
They don't always stutter, blush, or fuss.
This does not mean that liars are difficult to spot or to expose.
A skilled lie detector can get to the truth by observing the structure of statements, facial expressions, the structure of questions, and time characteristics.
I've spent several years researching scientific discoveries in the vast and ever-growing segment of knowledge about lying, and it's clear that lie detection is a modern skill that's easy to learn and that helps you navigate in our complex world -- especially if your professional responsibilities include recruiting, interviewing, negotiating, or managing.
Good liars are excellent at reading others, making them feel at ease, managing their own emotions and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men lie more about themselves, while women lie more about others, usually to protect someone else's feelings, that married people lie less to their partners than unmarried people (but the lies they tell are the most outrageous).
We also know that if you're perceived as a cheat, others will feel less guilty about cheating you.
How can you tell if someone is lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of your subject.
It's called "determining the initial state".
This helps provide a starting point for evaluating the change further.
Watch your subject's posture, laughter, vocal characteristics.
You'd do well to know if a person is tapping their feet constantly in a normal state, then you wouldn't be making unfair accusations when you see foot tapping in the middle of a meeting.
Then look for groups of deceptive verbal and nonverbal actions.
Treat these groups as red flags, not as evidence of deception.
The deceivers can fixate on their upper body when they try to recall their story, they can put their feet towards the door, lean towards the exit, change their posture in a certain way, or show "after-interview relief" -- this exaggerated sigh of relief and posture change when all the difficult questions are behind us.
Investigators often fake the end of an interview to just look at it as relief after the interview.
Now, pay attention to your subject's speech.
Scott Peterson is known to have stumbled and used the past tense to claim that his murdered wife was alive, leading to a nationwide search for her.
People who are craving may also use distance in speech: "I did not have sexual relations with this woman ... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a complex question completely.
The most typical verbal indicators are barely perceptible.
Someone may use "qualifying language" when answering a difficult question: "Well ... to be honest ... as far as I know ... as far as I know".
This makes the response more emotional than factual, and is often a red flag.
There is no magic tool to detect lies, but the skill of deception detection can be mastered.
These skills will increase the chances of everyone not becoming a victim of skilled fraudsters in their professional and personal lives.
