In addition to the decline in economic activity and high unemployment rate, 2011 saw the largest outflow of foreign direct investment in 10 years, according to the Ministry of Finance, with FDI in the state from January to July amounting to $630,697, which shows a decline of 87.74 percent compared to $5,143,312 during the same period last year.
For its part, the Ministry of Economic Development of the state government recorded a total of 17,280,000 pesos of investments during the year, which mainly came from companies in the service sector.
The debt
Amid the economic downturn, the state government asked in July for approval of a 3 billion pesos loan at the state congress to be used for infrastructure investments in 18 municipalities to revive the economy, only 2,600 million pesos were approved locally, and no debt benefits were expected in any sector of the state's economy until November.
The reaction
For business, the first year of the Mario Lopez Valdés government is a sign of the government's lack of capacity.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of Manufacturing Industry, said that during 2011, there was a lack of coordination between the various sectors, including the state government itself.
"The efficiency of the economy in Sinaloa this year was really low, we have to work hard to recover the positions lost this year, in 2012 we have to double our efforts, we have not been able to coordinate the efforts of all and, above all, the good and synchronized work of the new government team, we hope that next year will be much better", he said.
The slowdown in the economy
Lopez Loredo said events such as the early frosts this year have stunted the state's economy and limited its efficiency and growth.
"The low volumes of the economy are the result of several events, including frosts, one of the main effects was a slow economy that does not get fast enough to create an economic dynamic that allows to have an acceptable level of processes, goods and services and, therefore, at the end of the year we close it below our expectations", he said.
Revising the direction
Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederation of Mexican Employers in Sinaloa, said the state needs to continue its most dynamic production activity.
"In general, we found that we were working on this, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program that will redefine the direction and economic course of the state, it is necessary to mobilize all the material and human resources that Sinaloa has", he said.
Upcoming work
President Coparmex stressed the importance of defining the future direction to better direct the efforts of the government.
"In general, I would say that the Government is trying to be successful in various areas, in terms of economic development there is little progress, but it is important to develop a long-term program", he said.
He noted that the current administration has demonstrated progress in its own manner of conducting public policy.
"There are facts that allow us to say that the government is getting involved, and that I can say that some work has been done, and I think the government is aware that there is still a lot to do", he said.
