Mexico's "digital TV switchover" to be approved by court in 2015
The shift from analog to digital is one of the most important changes that the world has seen in recent years.
The Supreme Court (SC) has rejected constitutional challenges by the Senate and the House of Representatives against the presidential decree that postpones the so-called "digital television transition" from 2021 to 2015, as it did not receive the eight votes needed to overturn it.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Mesa, felt that President Felipe Calderón had not exceeded his authority by issuing a decree detailing the actions to be taken to transition to digital terrestrial television.
As a result, the constitutional claims made by the Senate were rejected for lack of the qualified majority of eight votes required for the court to rule on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and it remains in force.
The draft statement prepared by Minister Olga Sanchez Cordero proposed declaring the decree unconstitutional because the regulation of radio and television programming is a right enshrined in law by the Federal Commission on Telecommunications (Cofetel), in violation of the principles of hierarchical subordination and legislative reserve.
Only Salvidar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted in favour of the project, which was approved by the National Assembly.
On this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies held two constitutional debates to refute the decree and support the complaints, Minister Sanchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all actions mentioned in it regarding the transition to digital broadcasting.
The meeting of ministers also decided to reject the demand of the Chamber of Deputies without entering into the discussion of the project, also under the responsibility of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the prime minister said that he disagreed with the arguments of the project in the sense that the federal executive power could not define by general rules the measures for which the state administration should prepare.
"I also don't think that if it happened, it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body", and reminded that the planning of public policy in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is relevant to the federal executive, which has a constitutional mandate to govern the state.
The replacement of analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes that has happened in recent years, resulting in better use of the radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
Postponing the transition, he said, would mean postponing the benefits of digital transformation, which includes meeting societal needs that have more than just a technical dimension, "since it covers economic, social, political and national security issues".
These issues, he said, "require the work of the entire system, formed on the principle of state economic management, includes a group of authorities that the Constitution combines into the state executive power".
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the transition to digital broadcasting, and have done so with the help of the executive branch, despite the existence of narrowly-specific technical institutions.
It cannot be concluded from this that the government, by passing the decree under discussion, which in any case touches the competence of the Congress, ensures the compliance in the administrative sphere of the laws adopted by the Legislative Assembly, he said.
Michoacán is analyzing the possibility of counting "vote by vote"
According to the data provided to the VAR, the difference between the first and second place in the gubernatorial elections is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes, which comes to 879 out of the total number in 6,074 protocols.
The possibility of a "vote-for-vote" count is real, as it is in the process of this year's election in Michoacán, where, according to data obtained from the Preliminary Election Results Program (PERP), the difference between the first and second place in the gubernatorial election is only 27 percent, even without the counting of the votes, which comes to 879 out of a total of 6,074 minutes.
In this context, the president of the General Council of the Instituto Electoral de Michoacan (IEM), Maria de los Ángeles Llanderal Saragossa, recalled that a few days ago, on November 9, the electoral body approved a package of principles to harmonize local rules with federal electoral reform.
As a reminder, Michoacan did not adopt the Constitution or the state Electoral Code or the Voting Rights Act, as the state Congress approved the reforms shortly before the legal deadline for their enactment in this election process and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel did not include its publication in the deadline indicated in the law in the state's Official Gazette, saying that he had some objections.
On the same day, November 9, the Supreme Court of Justice (SCJ) ruled on a constitutional claim brought by the local legislature and called the state representative's vote on constitutional reform "invalid and illegal" as he had no right to "permit or support them".
In an interview about the possibility of "vote for vote", Maria de los Angeles Lyandeal argued that with the adoption of appropriate principles by the General Council of the IWM, it would be possible to present a partial or full count of votes by the local electoral body.
Thus, a partial recount of one or more ballot boxes may be made when: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there is no voting and counting record in the ballot box or it is not in the chairman's possession; or when there are obvious errors or corrections in the record.
In addition, a general recount of votes in all ballot boxes may be carried out when there is evidence that the difference between the presumed winner of the election in question and the runner-up is less than or equal to one percent, provided that a request is made at the beginning of the session by a representative of the party and/or coalition which has put forward the latter of the candidates.
A total recount will also be made if, at the end of the ordinary recount, it is found that the difference between the winner and the runner-up is less than or equal to one percent, provided that there is a request from the political party whose candidate came second, in the event that ballot boxes that were included in the partial recount are excluded.
It is worth noting that in such a situation is the election in Morelia, where, according to the PPRV, the difference between the first and second place is only 0.16 percent, not even counting 129 votes out of a total of 923 in the protocol.
His last will and testament .
His ashes will be scattered in the Sapaliname mountains, the family confirms.
The remains of pilot Felipe Basio Cortés arrived in Saltillo, his hometown, on Sunday evening; a funeral mass was held on Monday.
