After receiving condolences along with other people who died in the disaster, the Basio Cortes family returned to the capital of Coahuila aboard a Mexican Air Force aircraft, with their closest people attending the ceremony in Campo Marte.
At noon, the lieutenant colonel's ashes were taken to the chapel located on the Boulevard Nazario Ortiz Garcia, where family and friends were gathered.
At 5:30 p.m., he was seen by the Santillo Institute of Technology, organized by his former high school classmates and the football team that Felipe Bassio was a member of while in high school.
"His wish was to return to Saltillo and have his ashes scattered in the Sapalinama mountains, he always said this to his family and friends", said Sandra Cortes Bassio, the pilot's sister.
In her opinion, the lieutenant colonel fulfilled all her dreams, she believes that he was at the peak of his life, "he was a successful man, an incredible father, son and loving brother, devoted to his family".
Felipe Cortes Basio left Saltillo at a very young age to attend the College of Aviation in Sappopan, Jalisco.
Some didn't believe him, they said he was dizzy even in the truck, but he always wanted to fulfill his dream of becoming a pilot.
His nephew Jorge Alberto Davila Bacio remembers him as a very good man, "as soon as he arrived in Saltillo, the whole family wanted to welcome him, as when he brought Marta Saagún to Saltillo".
Juno remembers that even when he was seven, he went to Sapporo to attend the graduation ceremony of his cousin, so he knows that his uncle died doing what he loved most in life: flying a plane.
He's being escorted to his final destination.
Gunshots rang out in honor of Mexican Air Force Lieutenant Colonel Felipe Cortes Bassio, led by Governor Jorge Torres López, people from the village and state government, the Mexican Army, from the Sixth Military Zone, the Mexican Air Force itself, the leaders and students of the Technological High School in Saltillo, where he studied in 1985 and made progress in both studies and sports, accompanied him to the last.
Bassio Cortes died recently when the helicopter he was flying crashed, along with the Secretary of the Provincial Government, José Francisco Blake Morey, and six others, all representatives of this ministry.
At 6:05 p.m., the remains of Basío Cortes (cremated), a resident of Saltillo, arrived to be handed over to the funeral home by members of the Mexican Air Force, led by Major James Martinez, on the training school's esplanade, where his family, including his daughter Amanda and his wife Cristina, her mother, brothers and other relatives, students and teachers, were already waiting for him.
