The new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday.
The newly appointed Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet with the Italian President tomorrow to present a new government that will face the crisis that has brought the country to the brink of economic disaster.
Italy's newly appointed Prime Minister, Mario Monti, will meet with the Italian President on Wednesday to unveil a new government that will face the crisis that has brought Italy to the brink of economic collapse and has damaged the entire eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace said that Monti, who was appointed on Sunday, would meet on Wednesday with President Giorgio Napolitano to confirm that he could form a government.
He is expected to introduce a cabinet made up mostly of technocrats, though it is unclear when the new executive will take up his post.
Monti said he'd present the president with the results of his negotiations with the political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to reiterate my full confidence in the ability of our country to get through this difficult period", the former European commissioner told reporters.
Monty didn't say directly that he was able to form a government, but the tone of his comments showed that the obstacles had been overcome.
"The structure is now well defined", he said.
Monti completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much less than usual, as Italy struggled with a political and financial crisis that had brought their debt levels to a critical level.
The administration, led by former European Commissioner Monti, must approve the austerity package demanded by European leaders to restore Italy's credibility.
Under pressure from Monti to hurry, volatile markets set the yield on Italy's BTP bonds at 10 years over 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to be bailed out.
Emma Marcheglia, the leader of the Italian Employers' Federation, told reporters after meeting with Monti: "We said we would actively support this government".
We believe this government is Italy's last chance to get out of this crisis.
Monti's chances of success were largely based on support for the LDP party of Silvio Berlusconi, who was forced to resign on Saturday because of the crisis.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts should lead to a good outcome", said Angelino Alfano, secretary of the center-right party.
The support of the LDP, the largest party in Italy, is significant because until now many of its members have opposed the technocratic government majority that Monti is forming.
Parliamentary support
The new Monti government must have strong parliamentary support to carry out reforms that will likely be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blocking or halting of these attempts could lead to a new and devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks has stepped up the pressure, warning that the failure of Monti could be disastrous.
Monti began his consultations with political parties, unions and business groups, as well as youth and women's organizations, on Monday.
He'll finish his series of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who authorized an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite late last week when it became clear that Berlusconi would step down, the value of Italy's debt has now reached a critical level amid uncertainty over whether the new prime minister will be successful.
A bailout of Italy with a public debt of €1.8 billion would be too much for the modern financial defenders of the eurozone.
Monti said his government would exist until the next elections scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians would only give him time to carry out reforms before calling new elections.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the main parties insist that it should be made up of technical experts only, a sign of their dissatisfaction that the process is affected by the financial situation.
Political sources have reported that mutual distrust and disagreement between the parties are making it difficult to include political figures.
