The quintet has embarked on a tour of the country in honor of the twentieth anniversary of the career
'A trip to Costa Rica is a dream come true'
In an exclusive interview with Viva, Pearl Jam bassist Jeff Ament said the band is ready to play one of their best shows ever next Sunday at the National Stadium.
It's been over 20 years in the making, but the band says it's also a dream come true for them to play in this country.
That was the claim of bassist and founder, Jeff Ament, who gave an exclusive interview to Viva from Brazil last week.
The band is on a tour of South America in honor of its twentieth anniversary and on Sunday, the 20th, will make its only stop in Central America.
They will perform at the National Stadium that day, starting at 7:30 p.m., along with the Los Angeles-based band The X and the local band Las Robertas.
This is an excerpt from a conversation that was decoded and made available online in The Nation.
For your Costa Rican fans, is it a dream come true that Pearl Jam is playing in Costa Rica?
Costa Rica is a dream come true for us, too.
This is only our second trip to South and Central America, and so far, so good.
I've only been to Costa Rica once, on vacation, it's a beautiful country, and I think we can stay there for a few days.
So we're very happy to bring our music there.
I ask this because there is a certain loyalty to the band; the fans live in tension in the days before the concert.
What would you say to your most loyal fans?
Thank you for being with us all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica, thank you for waiting so long, and we're sorry it took us so long to get here.
Some people, in anticipation of your concert, are treating it as the biggest show of the year.
Does that add a little tension to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we've played in the last 21 years have been in the last two weeks.
We've had some great shows in São Paulo and we hope that's put us in shape for this gig in Costa Rica.
We really want to play here.
We love this country, we love surfing and jungle, and as far as those two things go, Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you know about Costa Rica and its surf waves?
We have a lot of surfer friends, and I have a good friend who lives in Tamarindo, and the waves are incredible.
My friends always go surfing to Costa Rica and Nicaragua and Mexico, and these are great places to surf, and this is how we learned about it, from people who love to surf.
From the tour, I can tell you've put on a show with a lot of songs.
What are you planning to do in Costa Rica?
Since we've never played there before, we have no limits to what we can do.
We're going to try to make the best show possible with the most diverse songs; we're going to try to play a few songs from each album and present our fans with a great variety of repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
How does that work?
I think part of the reason is that we have nine records and we can play over 120 songs, and everyone has a different taste in music, so it's hard to pick which songs to play every night.
When we have two or three songs that we haven't played in a while, it keeps us tuned in and surprises us, because it reminds us of the reasons why we loved those songs and what we might have forgotten.
It makes the show more interesting for us and therefore, I think, makes it more interesting for people.
You're celebrating 20 years of career with this tour.
Looking back, is it hard to believe all that you've done?
Yes, of course.
First of all, I don't think any of us could have ever imagined that we'd be in a rock band, and the fact that we've been doing this for over 20 years makes it seem like a dream.
We're happy with our luck and we're very excited that we can continue to make music together.
We all love each other and we all love making music.
We're happy to go places in the world we've always wanted to go.
Things are working out very well for us.
What does it mean to you to be a significant part of the grunge boom?
It's always been an honor to be a part of this group of great collectives.
We're good friends with the guys from Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It's great when a movement starts with a group of friends, and that's unusual.
From time to time, one group from the same city appears, but it's much more bizarre when five or ten groups appear at the same time in the same city.
We are proud and honored to be a part of the Seattle group.
I still play with some of them now and then.
Last year we were at the festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on tour, so we're happy to be friends with all of them and we're honored to be a part of the Seattle sound that's come out of it.
It's also very strange that a group like yours has stayed together and in the same lineup for so long.
Yeah, the four of us have been together for 21 years, and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which is way longer than most bands have been around.
One, I think we're lucky to be alive, and two, we care about others.
We're all very close friends, and because of that, we've also opened up musical avenues that give everyone the freedom to experiment.
We trust each other's music, and it couldn't be better.
Your relationship with fame was not easy; but thanks to your success, you were able to do everything you wanted.
How do you find the balance?
As we got older, it became easier to find balance.
We make sure we don't stay on the road too long, because it's easy to get into this game of big crowds and people who love your music.
As long as you remember that people are here for the music, it reminds you that you have to respect the music and what it's made of, not the decision to be famous and to be a rock star, which is something that none of us really care about.
How do you remember your other project, Manother Love Bone?
I think we write really good songs, and it was great in the beginning.
We were a band for almost three years and didn't release a single album until Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
There were a lot of disappointments because it had been so long, and the important thing is that we're still very close friends with Bruce and Greg, who started with us in the band, and when I hear a song or see a picture, I think about the amazing person that Andy was, and how he made me laugh, and it was always fun to go to work, and laugh, and talk about music and football and stuff.
He was a wonderful man, and we miss him.
The local band Las Robertas will be responsible for opening the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you're familiar with her work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose her to open?
Yeah, the producers sent us some video offers, and this was the band we liked the most, so we can't wait to see what Las Robertas have to offer live, and it should be very exciting.
Why do you keep changing the words to Yellow Ledbetter at concerts?
It's a question for Ed, so I don't know.
He's singing it and I think he's using whatever comes to mind.
Who influenced you as a bass player?
There's so many of them.
Some of the first names that come to mind are Heather Butler, John Entwisle, C.J. Ramon, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Ducowski...
There are so many I could talk about all the bass players I love all day.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep the grunge going, even though it's no longer in vogue?
I think we all feel a certain detachment from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of the bands I mentioned earlier, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others that came out around the same time, and if that's important now, I think it's great, because it's music worth listening to, and bands like Mudhoney are making music better than ever.
Your music was more somber at first, but now it's more positive.
How do you explain this change?
It's interesting because, I think, there are some songs on the album that might seem lighter, but there are songs like The End or Just Breathe that are considered very dark, although they can sound a little bit positive.
Both of them, when Ed played them, I cried when I heard them, these songs are very dark.
I think that when you're growing up and you've had some kind of trauma in your life and you've lost a family member or a friend, those events start to affect your creativity and your music, and these two songs, of course, reflect that for me.
So I think you can be a happy person and still be able to make dark music.
Peru:
Fuhimori was hospitalized again for medical examination
Former president Alberto Fujimori was admitted to a state hospital on Tuesday to be examined for a loss of muscle strength in his legs, his family doctor said.
Fuhimori, 72, who is serving a 25-year prison sentence for human rights abuses committed during his rule (1990-2000), suffers from several ailments, including tongue cancer, for which he has been operated on four times and is under observation.
Congressman Alejandro Aginag, who is his personal physician, told N TV that Fujimori will be examined in three days at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases to determine the cause of the pain and loss of strength in his lower extremities.
Aginaga said that in his opinion, Fujimori should be a candidate for a pardon on humanitarian grounds; however, he said that he did not want to do so because he knew he was innocent.
He had four surgeries for tongue cancer, lost 18 kilograms in weight, and had other ailments, such as severe erosive gastritis, pancreatic cysts, kidney stones, high blood pressure, and circulation problems in his legs, the doctor listed.
Fuhimori has been in prison since September 2007, in the Police National Special Operations Unit.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the murder of 25 people by the army's destruction squad, which operated in secret during the first years of his rule.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political ties
An official delegation headed by Uruguayan President José Mujica and consisting of several ministers and businessmen will arrive this Tuesday with a visit to Mexico to expand trade between the two countries and to begin talks on the political problems of the region.
Mujica will meet his Mexican counterpart, Felipe Calderón, next Wednesday, the most important item of a wide-ranging plan of meetings with political, commercial authorities and meetings with the Uruguayan community living in Mexico, according to a schedule published by the Uruguayan leadership.
The meeting of the two presidents in the city of Guadalajara will be "favorable for the exchange of information on the issue of political relations between the two nations", as published by the leadership of the South American country on its website.
According to local media, Mujica is seeking Calderon's support for Uruguay in the incident with France that occurred when French President Nicolas Sarkozy included the South American country on a list of tax havens at the G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that remain tax havens, a statement that provoked a protest in Uruguay and a recall for consultations of his ambassador in the European country.
Mexico has been chairing the G20 since November, a group made up of the most highly developed and developing countries, and has, in fact, had a tax information exchange agreement with the South American country since January of this year to avoid double taxation.
The government of Uruguay has been trying in recent years to speed up the conclusion of tax swaps agreements in order to leave this "grey list" of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development, made up of countries that do not use international tax cooperation standards.
As for the trade plan, Mexico and Uruguay have had a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) in place since 2004, which has increased trade between the two countries.
