MSS announces program to search for gene of obesity
Social Protection leads research to find the gene of obesity in children and young people; it is supported by experts from the IPN
The Mexican Social Security Institute (MSSI) announced that it is conducting a study to detect the gene of obesity in children and young people, which has been named the "Genetics of Obesity in Childhood and Adolescence" protocol, which will provide a count of signs associated with excess weight.
In his statement, Miguel Cruz López, head of the Biochemistry Division of the Hospital Especializado del Centro Médico Nacional del Siglo XXI, explained that a multidisciplinary team of therapists, nurses, dietitians and social workers had been assembled.
This team is supported by specialists and graduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (NIPH) and the Center for Scientific Research and Higher Education (CINVESTAV) of the National Polytechnic Institute (NPI).
The public (registered or not) is invited to participate by visiting the MSSI Sports Centers participating in the study in the Valley of Mexico, where tests will be conducted with children every Saturday morning at 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol began at the sports center in Cuautemoc (in the west of the state of Mexico), and since October 8 the events are held in the sports center in Nesahualcoyotl (east of the state of Mexico).
Once the target of 500 to 600 children has been reached, the study will continue at Independencia Sports Center (south of Mexico City) and finally at Morelos Sports Center (north of Mexico City).
He explained that the purpose of this study is to understand the components and importance of genetics in the development of obesity and to identify a risk factor among children and adolescents in Mexico to prevent the occurrence of chronic degenerative diseases.
November 14th is World Diabetes Day, and the main goal is to get 3,000 children and adolescents between the ages of 6 and 14 years old, with parental consent and supervision, to complete individual nutrition questionnaires.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases to avoid risk factors that lead to diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that on Saturday, anthropometric measurements of all participants (weight, height and waist circumference), blood pressure and glucose, fat, cholesterol and insulin levels, and genetic analysis (to identify genes that are associated with childhood obesity) would be carried out.
Cruz Lopez said the study reflects health professionals' concern about the alarming increase in childhood obesity.
Medical studies conducted between 1999 and 2006 show that in just 6 years, there was a rise: 77 percent of boys were obese, 47 percent of girls; as for excess weight, there was also a significant rise", said the MSSI specialist.
He said the rationale for finding markers was based on the fact that the population of the country was different from other peoples because of its genetic history.
He reported that the average Mexican is 65 percent Native American, 30 percent European, and five percent African, and that this condition affected genes that are associated with diabetes and obesity.
He explained that the main cause of obesity's genetics is the body's inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories), and it's stored as fat.
The researcher explained that the immediate benefit for the participants is the comprehensive evaluation of the children, which can reveal whether they have any degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark wrinkles on the neck and forearms means the likelihood of metabolic disorders and even prediabetes.
The information is handled with the utmost confidentiality, the doctors give it in writing to the parents, to whom they explain all the measurements and lifestyle changes that must be taken to avoid the disease.
Cruz Lopez explained that there are three main causes of overweight, obesity, and other chronic diseases: a sedentary lifestyle, or lack of daily physical activity, spending most of the day at home watching TV, and using public transportation for short distances instead of walking.
It also happens because of high calorie consumption, which means an increase in the consumption of sugary drinks and carbohydrates (tamale, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and genetic predisposition, analyzed in this program.
UNAM asphalt will be able to avoid cracks
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the UNAM's Department of Chemistry, has developed a polymer-modified bitumen to produce a blend of the highest quality, resistant to environmental and temperature influences.
If the signals sent by the pavement were taken into account, it would be necessary to repair about 200,000 holes for each rainy season in the metropolitan area of the Valley of Mexico, says Rafael Herrera Najera, a researcher at the UNAM's Department of Chemistry, adding that if the construction and maintenance of the asphalt pavement were correct, the number of holes could be reduced or even reduced to zero.
In his lecture, Technology View of Pits, delivered as part of the International Year of Chemistry, it is reported that the laboratory he is responsible for is developing a polymer-modified bitumen for the production of a mixture with characteristics close to bitumen, but with better resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Errera Najera said that this type of modified bitumen could be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, like some cities in the north, to improve the quality of the roads and therefore counteract the formation of pits.
He explained that bitumen, the heaviest part of oil, is a sequence of hydrocarbon molecules, some high-molecular-weight, called asphaltenes, and some low-molecular-weight, called maltenes, which together give the road surface its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
Bitumen's viscous behavior lies in the fact that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 its viscosity is very high, and at 50 degrees Celsius it retains an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures bitumen becomes brittle, he said.
This means that the resistance of the asphalt is not constant, but changes throughout the day, depending on the natural conditions and temperature, said a chemical engineering specialist.
A chemist has observed that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered with a flexible coating made up of six layers of material, the last three of which include bitumen.
Among the uppermost layers is bitumen, which is made up of small stones that are lowered into the bitumen and then pressed.
Every stone that makes up that coating, he said, is soaked in bitumen.
When moving vehicles and applying effort, this helps to distribute forces very well on the road surface.
If it was modified asphalt, they would be even better distributed, said the chemical engineer.
On top of the asphalt, he added, is a last layer, called the wear layer, which is made of fine stone, actually sand also immersed in asphalt.
Since this is the layer that will be in contact with the wheels of the vehicle, it must have greater resistance than the asphalt and provide road friction.
As part of the road surface that will receive and distribute this stress, the wear layer also requires proper thickness, and the material from which it is made must be taken into account.
Weather, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are also very important factors to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the condition of the asphalt.
When the soil is wet, water penetrates the coating and has difficulty getting out, causing all the layers of the coating to soften and, therefore, to form pits.
When pits are formed, he said, the first layer of wear and tear is applied and only then does it affect the bitumen, but the damage is not instantaneous, a process that should be addressed at the first signs of ongoing repair programs.
Also, a member of the National Research System explained that the transport load is another important factor in the formation of holes, and therefore the thickness of each coating layer should always be associated with the transport load and it is necessary to guarantee the fulfillment of this requirement to prevent the frequent occurrence of holes.
Rafael Herrera said that there is still a lot to be studied and done about bitumen, for example, bitumen emulsions, which in other countries are already on the market and even help to repair pits with ease and without the use of high temperatures.
