Japan Rebuilt After the Earthquake
GDP grew by 1.5% on the back of domestic consumption, ending a downturn that began in March
Since last March, the Japanese economy has been paralyzed and is still recovering from the devastating earthquake that triggered the nuclear crisis, the worst disaster to hit the Land of the Rising Sun since World War II.
The Tokyo government's initial estimate of the damage was $300,000,000,000 - a blow that, despite the dire global situation, seems to be passing.
After three consecutive losing quarters, July to September gross domestic product figures have definitely helped turn the page: GDP grew by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and 6% year-on-year.
Recorded in the second quarter, the Japanese fiscal year starts in March 2012 also represents the fastest growth rate from January to March 2010.
The revival may be partly explained by the revival of the purchase of machinery to rebuild areas devastated by the earthquake and subsequent tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investment by 1.1% against a 0.9% decline in capital expenditure seen from January to March, the first decline after six months of continuous growth.
But the true breakthrough in the Japanese economy is not based solely on the Keynesian impulse to use the crisis to strengthen - or restructure - infrastructure, using the gaps to grow from scratch.
Japan has awakened, largely due to the rise of household consumption, which now accounts for 60% of Japanese GDP.
This figure increased by 1% due to the increase in spending on cars, travel and leisure.
The seal of the yen
Tokyo has given the domestic market a privilege that is crushing the accounts of exporting companies, as the yen, the Japanese currency, has become one of the "refuge currencies" chosen by investors who want to get rid of the eurozone debt crisis and negative forecasts regarding the United States.
