The introduction of the "golden rule" of the budget into the constitution
The leadership of the grand coalition of social democrats and Christian democrats in power in Austria decided on Tuesday to write the budgetary "golden rule" into the constitution to reduce the budget deficit and thus avoid a possible downgrade of Austria's public credit rating (triple A) by rating agencies.
Chancellor Werner Feimann, a Social Democrat, announced the decision personally at the end of the cabinet meeting, with Austria's public debt at 74.6%, well above the upper 60% norm set by the Maastricht Treaty, but below the public debt of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
