Energy policy:
Facts should prevail over dogma .
If there is one issue that cannot be decided by a short debate or by an emotional one, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affects the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It's a healthy trend that the election is becoming a time to reflect on the role and place of nuclear power.
The debate will not bear fruit until all the economic, social and environmental implications of the options proposed have been examined.
France must base its opinion on objective facts and rational data.
With seven billion people on the planet today, the demographic growth will double the demand for electricity by 2050, unless a huge portion of the world's population is deprived of the vital elements.
During the same period, it will be necessary to fill the growing fossil resource deficit to continue to produce electricity continuously, not forgetting the crucial need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate imbalances - a topic that has disappeared from the environmental debate.
The Fukushima accident doesn't change any of those factors.
That's why Germany is alone in its decision to abandon nuclear power.
This is not the case with Belgium, which is making its decision based on the need to find a source capable of replacing nuclear energy, or with Switzerland, which is planning to build only the most advanced reactors.
On the other hand, the United Kingdom, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil - these are just a few of the countries that are pursuing their projects with determination.
The United States decided to add one more to its kit after Fukushima, resuming construction of a station that had been suspended after the accident at Three Mile Island.
Although the German renewable energy model is sometimes cited as an example, the reality contradicts this argument.
The Berlin Wall will result in higher electricity costs, increased energy dependence, exacerbated by an increased demand for imported gas, particularly from Russia, and a surge in carbon dioxide emissions from the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, all these unpleasant effects will be felt.
Consider the example of Denmark.
Europe's champion in turbine construction, from which it derives 30% of its electricity, it is also the largest consumer of coal and gas due to its intermittent wind; which has caused carbon dioxide emissions and electricity prices to be 65% and 50% higher, respectively, than the European average.
On the other hand, thanks to our consistent energy policy, our neighbours pay 40% more for electricity than French households.
Since in a globalised economy the price of energy is a key factor of competitiveness and the key to the maintenance of industrial equipment on national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
Consequently, any significant reduction in nuclear power will lead to a large increase in the cost of electricity, which will make the beautiful claims of our country's new industrialization and consumer protection illusory.
A price that most French people refuse to pay, especially since they don't object to this type of energy in principle.
It should be recalled that the country's energy policy has made it possible to create an industry with 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Strongly export-oriented, it attracts a whole host of small and medium-sized enterprises specialising in international trade and creates many jobs that cannot be moved to another industry.
If France decided to abandon nuclear energy, it would have to sacrifice a large number of these enterprises and lose 6 billion euros a year in French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
What electrical engineer would order an EPR designed to last 60 years if his manufacturer was scheduled to close?
To solve the energy equation, we must recognize that there is no divine or diabolical source of energy.
Areva's development of low carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions is a testament to the complementarity of energy sources.
For nuclear power, maintaining the highest level of safety is a matter of vital importance.
In France, we have a security agency that exercises uncompromising and transparent control over existing energy centres such as Flamenville.
Our teams, whose professionalism is universally recognized, are filled with the same obsession with safety.
In the last 50 years, the nuclear industry has suffered three major accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, has occurred under normal operating conditions, but without any consequences to humans or the environment.
In Chernobyl, the design of the reactor and an unforgivable human error led to tragedy.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was the result of two natural disasters of unprecedented force that resulted in the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident, as it learned from the previous two.
The result of this step and the cooperation between the security authorities, operators and French and German designers, EPR, is a project that makes it possible to counter such phenomena.
As it is viewed by all energy professionals who wish to build a reactor, stopping construction at Flamanville would be a great gift to rivals Areva and EDF, clearing the way for them to take the lead in the inevitable development of nuclear power.
It is necessary and legitimate to seek the best combination of energy sources for our country, but it would be irresponsible to allow emotions, dogmas and biased maneuvers to prevail in a dispute that is so important for the economic, social and financial position of our country.
Immigration - a burden or a boon for the economy?
Immigration policy under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various angles - overloading police, judicial and administrative services, the subordination of the numbers policy and the compatibility of this policy with France's self-proclaimed status as a "human rights state".
Then there was the administrative harassment of foreign students, which made headlines when the Minister of the Interior (Liberation, May 23) declared that France "did not need foreign talents, masons and waiters".
But it's very rarely analyzed from an economic standpoint.
The right and the left agree on many points.
On the right, Jacques Chirac, who in 1976 said that "900,000 unemployed people would not be a problem in a country with 2 million foreign workers", and on the left, Michel Rocard, who explained in 1990 that France "cannot accept the poor of the world".
The only difference is the level of generosity.
In 2005, fear of the invasion of the Polish water supply system was felt by both the left and the right.
Both sides see immigration as a burden on the French economy and on French society.
The only difference is the level of generosity they are willing to show to immigrants.
In his program, François Hollande went beyond the platitudes, saying that "working together will solve our immigration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden and a problem can give you an electoral advantage, but it's very costly economically.
As economists Ian Goldin and Jeffrey Cameron remind us in their recent book summarizing the latest data on immigration (People of Distinction: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Determine Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is broad consensus among scholars about the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries that accept immigrants.
Restricting immigration leads to weaker growth and lower employment.
The fear of the influence of immigrants is based on the notion that they can replace local workers, especially those with low skills, and cause a decline in wages.
But experience shows that in reality, immigrants are far more likely to supplement than replace the local workforce by doing jobs that are lacking in the local workforce.
The unskilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract the local workforce, and the highly skilled in dynamic sectors where training is not linked to job offers.
Positive impact on wages
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country where there is a shortage of anaesthetists, the complementarity that exists between the locals and the immigrants results in the arrival of the immigrants having a positive impact on the wages of the local workers.
Giovanni Parry has calculated that a 1% increase in migration flow leads to a 0.6-0.9% increase in real long-term wages.
And this is not to mention the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants is a catalyst for new ideas and economic growth (a large share of the American Nobel Prize winners are naturalized immigrants, and Google, Intel, Paypal and Yahoo were all founded by immigrants).
Migrants also contribute a net benefit to the social security system, contributing on average 1% of the total budgets of European countries.
The World Labor Organization estimates that in Germany, for example, an immigrant who arrives at the age of 30 will bring an average net profit (income minus expenses) of 150,000 euros to the state budget during his or her lifetime.
Nicolas Sarkozy, at the beginning of his mandate, was going to "tooth" to cling to the missing growth points.
The teeth that were used to scare off immigrants had the exact opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, it is only a question of European democracy
Democracy is a valuable asset; it is also fragile.
The European continent must remember that, having invented it in Athens more than two thousand years ago, it has lived through the tragedies of World War I, totalitarian regimes, the Holocaust, the Gulag, Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal and the colonels in Greece.
Some felt that if democracy was to win the final victory over its enemies, it was enough to organize the voting and make it as direct as possible.
Ever since Napoleon the Small, it's been known that it comes from the surface of thinking.
Universal suffrage, while a necessary condition of democracy, is not a sufficient condition and may even become "an instrument of repression", as the Republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: public space, public spirit, values, organization, separation and control of powers, education, education, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis we are experiencing in Europe is an economic crisis, but it is first and foremost a political crisis and a crisis of democracy.
In this respect, the truth-or-false Greek referendum will have a double-edged revealing effect, demonstrating both the need for a major change in policy and the unpleasant feeling of its impossibility and inconsistency.
This duality needs to be understood to overcome it.
The truth is that the front line of the struggle for democracy has now shifted, and in the opinion of many, the Republican soldiers are now aiming in the wrong direction.
We gain nothing by demanding a series of national referendums organized as needed and in a haphazard manner.
Cart-blank for the absolute European monarch or a bound-legged plunge into the abyss of nationalism - what a choice for the citizen!
No, we do not dream of a guillotine blade, but of the implementation - joint, clear and continuous - of choice and democracy, this time at a pan-European level.
There is no crisis in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal, and it is not known how many more there are, because there is only one crisis, the European crisis.
The whole of Europe is being dictated by markets and rating agencies, suffering from its own weakness and lack of solidarity.
The whole of Europe is humiliated on the international stage.
Many are concerned about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe, but the whole of Europe is gradually losing its sovereignty, and with it each of its nations.
The European project must be brought back under the sovereignty of the people.
Because only by working together can Europeans reduce the burden of debt on each other, free themselves from markets and prepare for the future by investing in it.
The solution to the crisis will require decisions at pan-European level, and they cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, without leading us to disaster.
After much debate, the Socialists and Jacques Delors have proposed a European economic government.
Let it be.
But to imagine it without stronger economic, political and democratic integration, which has brought citizens to life, is another folly and a new dead end.
We must begin a new phase in the construction of Europe.
To establish a republic in France, you had to "create" republicans.
A revolution of interests would not be enough.
That lesson is still valid.
We must build a Europe that is economically united.
This can only be done by creating a more democratic Europe at the political level, a true European sovereignty of the people.
To create Europe, let us create the Europeans.
