The Nord Stream, a new gateway for Russian gas into Europe.
The Nord Stream pipeline, connecting Western Europe and Russia directly under the Baltic Sea, is now in operation.
It's designed to supply the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, Russia's largest gas producer, wanted to celebrate the occasion with a pump.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, attended last Tuesday's opening of the Nord Stream, a new gas pipeline that connects Russia and Germany directly underwater, on the shores of the Baltic Sea, between orchestra performances and fine dining.
German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Francois Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mart Rutte have together turned the symbolic valve that controls the flow of Russian gas into the Western European grid.
The new pipeline will provide an additional 27.5 million cubic meters of gas to Western Europe each year via the first pipeline, which will be 1,224 kilometers long and will connect the Leningrad region with the Mecklenburg-Pomerania land.
The second pipeline is expected to be completed by the end of 2012, providing a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, equivalent to all of France's consumption.
And the possibility of building a third pipeline in the same direction is already being discussed.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge project is a victory.
The project met with fierce resistance from Poland and the Baltic states.
Nord Stream will indeed allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, without having to go through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
The two countries will lose some of their power: it will be harder for them to influence Russia, threatening to close access to Western European markets.
