The construction of this pipeline is a technical feat.
The underwater pipeline is made of steel, encased in concrete to protect it from the anchors of ships.
It lies on the seabed, at an average depth of 200 meters.
To build it, we had to bypass the minefields left over from World War II.
"The clock had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution", said Jens Müller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
Many steps were also needed to protect the fauna and flora.
The pipeline is a long metal snake, equal in weight to 242 Eiffel Towers, with no breaks along its length, no vents and no service stations.
A control platform was planned for Sweden, but the project managers abandoned it because Sweden was not thrilled that a Russian state-owned company would permanently settle on its shores.
"In the event of an accident, we can cut off the gas in less than a minute", says Jens Muller.
So if there's a leak, the gas in the pipeline will be blown away.
But that seems unlikely to designers who designed seams that only leak once every 100,000 years.
The condition of the pipeline will be monitored by an underwater robot that the ship pulls for external observation, as well as by the apparatus circulating inside the pipeline.
The cigar-shaped apparatus is inserted into a pipe of 1 metre diameter and pushed forward by a gas flow.
Upon arrival after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, it gives accurate information about any deformation of the metal.
The pipeline was designed to operate for 50 years without the need for the slightest repair.
Gas circulation is only by its pressure.
It is 200 bar on departure and 100 bar on arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the capital.
The rest are German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), Dutch Gasunie and French Group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies formed a joint venture called Nord Stream, which was tasked with building and operating the pipeline.
Its headquarters are in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Then Gazprom gave this company a 20-year lease with the possibility of extending the entire volume of gas transportation.
"Gazprom will pay for the full amount, regardless of how much gas is actually transported", Jens Muller claims.
The construction of the pipeline was financed by 30% shareholders and 70% bank loans.
The total cost of the work will be 7.4 thousand million euros for the two pipelines.
GDF Suez's investment will be around 240 million.
The nano-military shareholders are confident that they will recoup their costs because Gazprom is taking all the risks.
The pipeline runs from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin to a sandy shore planted with coniferous trees.
The valves are 4.5 meters high and form the gas terminal.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas before it is pumped into German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal has been receiving one million cubic meters of gas every hour.
At full capacity, that's 3 million per hour, and in 2012, that's 6 million.
A Moleskine brand notebook .
Moleskine, created by an Italian company fifteen years ago, will bring back the flavor of writing.
It has the smell of adventure, of hours spent writing by candlelight.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognized by its rectangular black cover, by its gum, by its yellowish-white pages, as if they had turned yellow with time.
However, the Moleskine notebook as we know it today was born in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, has decided to launch designer notebooks.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, took responsibility for the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by the old production technique of moleskin, a lacquered cotton cloth used to cover benches, for example.
It is said that this type of notebook is highly prized by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine brought to the forefront of today's taste an old and forgotten thing that was a cult for avant-garde artists until the 20th century", said Maria Sebregondi, who has since become a brand manager at Modo Modo.
The luck is here.
From 2006 to 2010, sales increased by 25% to 12.7 million units.
We've come a long way from the early years, when there were only 3,000 notebooks produced.
Moleskine has crossed the Italian border and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the USA.
It's hard to profile a typical customer because the notebook appeals to businessmen, college students, and freelancers alike.
Moleskine's customers are cosmopolitan, broad-minded and educated.
The small Italian company, which started with only 12 employees, now has 100 and two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her notebooks in Fnac bookstores, small-town shops and has gained wide recognition.
"We followed the spirit of the times and this new need for writing, despite the advent of e-mail", explains Maria Sebregondi.
This distinctive cultural trait has accompanied Moleskine's development; the brand recently organized the "Round Road" exhibition, where architects and artists showcased their own block art.
In August, he also launched a leopard cover for the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and cultural aura, Moleskine has diversified its products, which now include handbags, pen, computer bags, and all kinds of support.
A success that generated envy: in the autumn of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, which wrote a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate among disabled workers so high?
Approximately 19% of disabled people are looking for work.
The 15th week of the employment of the disabled begins today.
Despite the public charity policy launched in 2005, the unemployment rate among the disabled is still twice the average, namely 19%, compared to 9% for the general population.
Discouraged you?
"No", says Eric Blanche, CEO of Adapt, the organization that organizes the Disabled Employment Week.
"In 15 years, we have made significant progress".
"At that time, the unemployment rate was not 2 but 3 times higher".
"But there is still much work to be done".
I have to say, there are still many obstacles to employment for a disabled person.
Among them, the elderly are more numerous: 37% are over 50 years old (average 17%).
They are more likely to be low-skilled: 80% do not have a bachelor's degree, and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 have disabilities.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very high, at 85% for the disabled, compared with 38% on average.
In short, these are all criteria that make it very difficult to return to work and that are at the heart of the problem", says Christian Grapen, CEO of Tremplin, an association set up in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
Here are some of the obstacles.
Needless to say, the mentality is changing, but too slowly.
A study commissioned by the Cité and carried out in April by the IMS-Entreprendre association showed that the managers surveyed had a low level of knowledge about disability and "imagined people in wheelchairs or mentally or intellectually disabled".
The result is that private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from the target of having 6% of employees with disabilities, set in a law passed in 1987.
The last known figures for 2008 are 2.6%.
"Today we are at about 3%", says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, an organization responsible for collecting taxes from companies that do not comply with the law.
Proof: the number of 'taxable' organisations, as well as the amounts paid, decreased in 2007-2011 from 59 000 to 46 000 organisations (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law that raised the tax put a lot of pressure on the companies", explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects a growing awareness, particularly in large enterprises".
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of organizations with 20 to 49 employees have disabled employees, compared to 82% of organizations with 100 to 199 employees.
